Study area. Specimens of sponges were collected along both the west and the south coasts of
South Africa
( Figure 1 ). The west coast is strongly influenced by the cool Benguela Current, and is characterised by a narrow continental shelf and coastal upwelling, which makes it a hydrodynamically active and productive region (
Hutchings et al . 2009
). The shelf along the south coast is much broader. Coastal upwelling occurs seasonally at capes and peninsulas, and shelf–edge upwelling occurs along the edge of the Agulhas Bank (
Hutchings et al . 2009
). Offshore, the warm Agulhas Current, which retroflects to flow eastwards south of Cape Agulhas, strongly influences water temperatures in the region. Whilst the Agulhas Current itself is not very productive, the waters over the Agulhas Bank are (
Hutchings et al . 2009
).

